The paper discusses the development of a language for writing specifications for programs that can operate in an open world setting, where the program interacts with external code and may evolve over time. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes a formal semantics for the language, which suggests that it may also belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category. The paper also discusses the necessary conditions for program components to function correctly, which suggests that it may belong to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category. The paper also discusses the robustness of programs, which suggests that it may belong to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes a language for writing specifications that can reason about the use of components, which suggests that it may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category.
